# Convex Best Practices

## Async/Await

- Always await all promises in Convex functions
- Never let promises float (e.g., `await ctx.scheduler.runAfter`, `await ctx.db.patch`)
- Use TypeScript ESLint `no-floating-promises` rule

## Database Queries

### Understand Convex `.filter()` vs JavaScript `.filter()`

**Convex `.filter()`** (database operation):
- Scans every document returned by the index
- Doesn't use indexes for filtering
- Poor performance for large result sets
- Should be replaced with compound indexes

**JavaScript `.filter()`** (in-memory operation):
- Standard Array method after `.collect()` or `.take()`
- Acceptable for complex logic not suitable for indexes
- Keep result sets small before filtering

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - Convex .filter() after index (scans all results)
const publishedClips = await ctx.db
  .query("clips")
  .withIndex("by_talk_id", (q) => q.eq("talkId", talkId))
  .filter((q) => q.eq(q.field("status"), "published")) // Database scan
  .collect();

// ✅ Good - Use compound index for filtering
const publishedClips = await ctx.db
  .query("clips")
  .withIndex("by_talk_id_and_status", (q) => 
    q.eq("talkId", talkId).eq("status", "published")
  )
  .collect();

// ✅ Good - JavaScript .filter() for complex logic (after fetching)
const items = await ctx.db
  .query("items")
  .withIndex("by_user", (q) => q.eq("userId", userId))
  .take(50); // Keep dataset small
const filtered = items.filter(item => 
  complexBusinessLogic(item) // Logic not suitable for index
);

// ⚠️ Avoid - JavaScript .filter() on large datasets
const allItems = await ctx.db.query("items").collect(); // Could be 10,000+
const filtered = allItems.filter(item => item.status === "active"); // Use index instead
```

**When to use each**:
- **Compound indexes**: For field equality/range checks (status, dates, IDs)
- **JavaScript `.filter()`**: For complex logic, calculations, or regex (after limiting dataset)
- **Never use Convex `.filter()`**: Except in rare pagination edge cases

**Exception**: Paginated queries (`.paginate()`) may benefit from Convex `.filter()` for fields not in index, but prefer compound indexes when possible.

### Limit `.collect()` usage

- Only use `.collect()` when returning small result sets (< 1000 documents)
- For large datasets, use indexes, pagination, limits, or denormalization
- All results count toward database bandwidth, even filtered ones

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - potentially unbounded
const allMovies = await ctx.db.query("movies").collect();

// ✅ Good - use index to filter first
const moviesByDirector = await ctx.db
  .query("movies")
  .withIndex("by_director", (q) => q.eq("director", "Steven Spielberg"))
  .collect();

// ✅ Good - use pagination
const watchedMovies = await ctx.db
  .query("watchedMovies")
  .withIndex("by_user", (q) => q.eq("user", userId))
  .paginate(paginationOptions);

// ✅ Good - use limit with UI fallback
const watchedMovies = await ctx.db
  .query("watchedMovies")
  .withIndex("by_user", (q) => q.eq("user", userId))
  .take(100);
const count = watchedMovies.length === 100 ? "99+" : watchedMovies.length.toString();
```

## Indexes

### Remove redundant indexes

- `by_foo` and `by_foo_and_bar` are usually redundant (keep `by_foo_and_bar`)
- An index on `["foo"]` is actually `["foo", "_creationTime"]`
- Exception: If you need to sort by `foo` and `_creationTime`, keep both

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - redundant indexes
schema.defineTable("teamMembers")
  .index("by_team", ["team"])
  .index("by_team_and_user", ["team", "user"]);

// ✅ Good - single compound index
schema.defineTable("teamMembers")
  .index("by_team_and_user", ["team", "user"]);
```

## Security

### Always use argument validators

- Use validators on all `query`, `mutation`, and `action` functions
- Consider return value validators too
- For `httpAction`, use zod or similar for validation

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - no validation
export const updateMessage = mutation({
  handler: async (ctx, { id, update }) => {
    await ctx.db.patch(id, update);
  },
});

// ✅ Good - validated arguments
export const updateMessage = mutation({
  args: {
    id: v.id("messages"),
    update: v.object({
      body: v.optional(v.string()),
      author: v.optional(v.string()),
    }),
  },
  handler: async (ctx, { id, update }) => {
    await ctx.db.patch(id, update);
  },
});
```

### Implement access control

- Check `ctx.auth.getUserIdentity()` for authenticated-only functions
- Use unguessable identifiers (UUID, Convex ID) for access control
- Never use spoofable values (email) for authentication
- Prefer granular functions (`setTeamOwner`) over generic ones (`updateTeam`)

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - no access control
export const updateTeam = mutation({
  args: { id: v.id("teams"), update: v.object({...}) },
  handler: async (ctx, { id, update }) => {
    await ctx.db.patch(id, update);
  },
});

// ✅ Good - checks auth
export const updateTeam = mutation({
  args: { id: v.id("teams"), update: v.object({...}) },
  handler: async (ctx, { id, update }) => {
    const user = await ctx.auth.getUserIdentity();
    if (user === null) throw new Error("Unauthorized");
    
    const isTeamMember = /* check membership */;
    if (!isTeamMember) throw new Error("Unauthorized");
    
    await ctx.db.patch(id, update);
  },
});
```

## Internal Functions

### Use `internal` for scheduled/called functions

- Functions called by `ctx.scheduler`, `ctx.run*`, or crons should be `internal`
- Never schedule or run public `api` functions
- Public functions need careful security auditing; internal functions don't
- Share code via helper functions, not by calling public functions

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - using api
crons.daily(
  "send daily reminder",
  { hourUTC: 17, minuteUTC: 30 },
  api.messages.sendMessage,
  { author: "System", body: "Share your daily update!" }
);

// ✅ Good - using internal
async function sendMessageHelper(
  ctx: MutationCtx,
  args: { body: string; author: string }
) {
  // shared implementation
}

export const sendMessage = mutation({
  args: { body: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, { body }) => {
    const user = await ctx.auth.getUserIdentity();
    if (!user) throw new Error("Unauthorized");
    await sendMessageHelper(ctx, { body, author: user.name ?? "Anonymous" });
  },
});

export const sendInternalMessage = internalMutation({
  args: { body: v.string(), author: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    await sendMessageHelper(ctx, args);
  },
});
```

## Code Organization

### Use helper functions for shared logic

- Write most logic as plain TypeScript functions
- Keep `query`, `mutation`, `action` wrappers thin
- Organize shared code in `convex/model/` directory
- Use TypeScript types: `QueryCtx`, `MutationCtx`, `ActionCtx`

```typescript
// ✅ Good structure
// convex/model/users.ts
import { QueryCtx } from '../_generated/server';

export async function getCurrentUser(ctx: QueryCtx) {
  const userIdentity = await ctx.auth.getUserIdentity();
  if (!userIdentity) throw new Error("Unauthorized");
  const user = await ctx.db.query("users")
    .withIndex("by_token", (q) => q.eq("token", userIdentity.tokenIdentifier))
    .unique();
  return user;
}

// convex/users.ts
import * as Users from './model/users';

export const getCurrentUser = query({
  args: {},
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    return Users.getCurrentUser(ctx);
  },
});
```

### Avoid `ctx.runAction` unless switching runtimes

- Replace `ctx.runAction` with plain TypeScript functions
- Only use `ctx.runAction` when calling Node.js code from Convex runtime
- Each `runAction` call has overhead (separate function, memory, CPU)

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - unnecessary runAction
export const scrapeWebsite = action({
  handler: async (ctx, { siteMapUrl }) => {
    const pages = /* parse sitemap */;
    await Promise.all(
      pages.map((page) =>
        ctx.runAction(internal.scrape.scrapeSinglePage, { url: page })
      )
    );
  },
});

// ✅ Good - plain TypeScript function
export async function scrapeSinglePage(
  ctx: ActionCtx,
  { url }: { url: string }
) {
  const page = await fetch(url);
  const text = /* parse page */;
  await ctx.runMutation(internal.scrape.addPage, { url, text });
}

export const scrapeWebsite = action({
  handler: async (ctx, { siteMapUrl }) => {
    const pages = /* parse sitemap */;
    await Promise.all(
      pages.map((page) => Scrape.scrapeSinglePage(ctx, { url: page }))
    );
  },
});
```

## Actions

### Minimize sequential `ctx.runQuery`/`ctx.runMutation` calls

- Each runs in separate transaction - may have inconsistent data
- Combine multiple calls into single query/mutation when possible
- Exception: Processing large datasets or side effects between calls

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - sequential queries (could be inconsistent)
const team = await ctx.runQuery(internal.teams.getTeam, { teamId });
const teamOwner = await ctx.runQuery(internal.teams.getTeamOwner, { teamId });

// ✅ Good - single query (guaranteed consistent)
const teamAndOwner = await ctx.runQuery(internal.teams.getTeamAndOwner, {
  teamId,
});

// ❌ Bad - loop with separate mutations
for (const member of teamMembers) {
  await ctx.runMutation(internal.teams.insertUser, member);
}

// ✅ Good - single mutation
await ctx.runMutation(internal.teams.insertUsers, teamMembers);
```

### Use `ctx.run*` sparingly in queries/mutations

- Prefer plain TypeScript functions over `ctx.runQuery`/`ctx.runMutation`
- Extra overhead compared to helper functions
- Exceptions:
  - Using components (require `ctx.run*`)
  - Need partial rollback on error

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - unnecessary ctx.runQuery
export const listMessages = query({
  handler: async (ctx, { conversationId }) => {
    const user = await ctx.runQuery(api.users.getCurrentUser);
    // ... rest of logic
  },
});

// ✅ Good - helper function
export const listMessages = query({
  handler: async (ctx, { conversationId }) => {
    const user = await Users.getCurrentUser(ctx);
    // ... rest of logic
  },
});

// ✅ Exception - partial rollback
export const trySendMessage = mutation({
  handler: async (ctx, { body, author }) => {
    try {
      await ctx.runMutation(internal.messages.sendMessage, { body, author });
    } catch (e) {
      // Records failure, but rollback sendMessage writes
      await ctx.db.insert("failures", { kind: "MessageFailed", error: `${e}` });
    }
  },
});
```

## Quick Reference Checklist

Before production:
- [ ] All promises are awaited
- [ ] No `.filter()` on queries (use indexes or code filters)
- [ ] `.collect()` only used with small result sets
- [ ] No redundant indexes
- [ ] All public functions have argument validators
- [ ] All public functions have access control checks
- [ ] Only `internal` functions are scheduled or called via `ctx.run*`
- [ ] Code organized with helper functions in `convex/model/`
- [ ] Minimal use of `ctx.runAction` (only for runtime switches)
- [ ] No sequential `ctx.runQuery`/`ctx.runMutation` in actions
- [ ] Limited `ctx.run*` in queries/mutations (prefer helpers)
